Introduction

The data set analyzed can be obtained from the kaggle platform.Global YouTube Statistics 2023. https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/nelgiriyewithana/global-youtube-statistics-2023

An collection of YouTube content creators, this dataset offers an ideal road to analyze and acquire valuable insights from the luminaries of the platform.

With comprehensive details on top creators’ subscriber counts, video views, upload frequency, country of origin, earnings, and more, this treasure trove of information is a must-explore for aspiring content creators, data enthusiasts, and anyone intrigued by the ever-evolving online content landscape.

With this extraordinary dataset, you can immerse yourself in the world of YouTube success and gain access to a wealth of information.

EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis) is an essential iterative process in data analysis. Analysts and data scientists use statistical and visualization techniques to explore, summarize, and uncover insights, patterns, and relationships within a dataset. It’s not a one-time task but a continuous and evolving process, allowing for a deeper understanding of data characteristics and structures as you delve further into the information. EDA is integral to data analysis, enabling data-driven decision-making and the identification of trends and key insights.

Data Understanding: View the first few rows of the dataset. Let’s check first 6 observations.

head(youtube)

Initial Exploration - EDA begins with a preliminary examination of the dataset. This includes visualizing basic statistics, distributions, and relationships among variables to gain an initial understanding of the data.

One common step is to use the str() function, which provides an overview of the dataset’s structure. It helps in obtaining a fundamental understanding of the dataset’s composition and variable types

str(youtube)

The dataset consists of 995 observations (rows) and 28 variables (columns). Among these variables, there are 7 character-type variables, 4 integer-type variables, and the remaining are numeric variables.

To prepare for meaningful visualizations, we plan to factorize certain variables, such as ‘category’ and ‘Country.’ Additionally, addressing missing values and filtering out extreme values will be essential for obtaining meaningful insights from the data.

To gain an initial overview of the dataset, we will utilize the ‘summary’ function. This function provides key summary statistics for integer and numeric variables, including measures such as the minimum, 1st quartile, median, mean, 3rd quartile, and maximum.

summary(youtube)

In the dataset, we encountered an issue with the ‘uploads’ variable, where the minimum value is recorded as 0. This presents a paradox, as it’s implausible for any YouTuber within the top 995 ranks to have never uploaded a video. To ensure the integrity of our analysis and avoid potential bias, we will address these erroneous values during data cleaning, as this step is crucial for producing accurate insights.

Additionally, we noticed that when we used the ‘summary’ function for character variables, there were no descriptions provided. To enhance the interpretability and consistency of our data, we will apply factorization to these categorical variables. This transformation will prove valuable when creating meaningful visualizations and drawing insights from the dataset.

During the exploratory data analysis (EDA) process, we began generating hypotheses. One noteworthy hypothesis is that content in the ‘Entertainment’ and ‘Music’ categories tends to generate higher revenue compared to other fields. This suggests that aspiring YouTubers aiming for substantial income may find it advantageous to consider these categories as a potential starting point. These hypotheses serve as valuable starting points for our analysis, guiding us towards deeper investigations and insights.

Initial Transformations

Data Type Conversion

# Convert 'below columns' to a factor (categorical) variable
youtube <- within(youtube, {
          category      <- as.factor(category)
          Country       <- as.factor(Country)
          channel_type  <- as.factor(channel_type)
          created_month <- as.factor(created_month)
})

Modifying the Column names & then cleaning the data

#There is a column name 'video views' whis is difficult yo use in ploting and also "Gross tertiary education enrollment (%)" that is big, we need to modify the column names.
colnames(youtube)[which(colnames(youtube) == 'video views')] <- 'video_views'
colnames(youtube)[which(colnames(youtube) == 'Gross tertiary education enrollment (%)')] <- 'Gross_Tertiary_Edu_Enrol'

#Gross_Tertiary_Edu_Enrol column states the %age population that has done education, this can never be more than 100%. So, changing all the values >100 to 100.
youtube <-
  mutate(youtube,
      Gross_Tertiary_Edu_Enrol = ifelse(Gross_Tertiary_Edu_Enrol >100, 100, Gross_Tertiary_Edu_Enrol))

As part of data preprocessing, we performed a data type conversion operation. Specifically, we created a new column by concatenating three existing columns: ‘Year,’ ‘Month,’ and ‘Date.’ This new column, which we named ‘new_date,’ allows us to represent dates in a standardized format. This transformation simplifies date-related operations and enhances the overall usability of the dataset.

youtube <- youtube %>%
  mutate(
    # Create a new column "new_date" by combining year, month, and date
    new_date_str = paste(created_year, created_month, created_date, sep = "-")
  )
# Convert the concatenated string to a Date object
youtube$new_date <- as.Date(youtube$new_date_str, format = "%Y-%b-%d")
youtube <- youtube |>
  relocate(new_date, .after = Longitude)
# Optional: Since we don't need the intermediate concatenated string I Removed it.
youtube <- youtube[, -ncol(youtube)]

In order to improve the visual structure and understanding of our dataset, we rearranged the columns. Our goal was to arrange related variables in a more intuitive and organized manner.

# Rearrange the columns for better visual understanding in tabular form

# First, rearrange the columns related to video views
youtube <- youtube |>
  relocate(video_views, .before = video_views_for_the_last_30_days)

# Next, relocate the 'channel_type' column to be near the 'category' column
youtube <- youtube |>
  relocate(channel_type, .before = category)

# Move the 'channel_type_rank' column to follow the 'channel_type' column
youtube <- youtube |>
  relocate(channel_type_rank, .after = channel_type)

# Move the 'country_rank' column to follow the 'Abbreviation' column
youtube <- youtube |>
  relocate(country_rank, .after = Abbreviation)

# Add a new 'Rural_Population' column by subtracting 'Urban_population' from 'Population'
youtube <- youtube |>
  mutate(Rural_population = Population - Urban_population)

# Rearrange the columns for 'Population,' 'Urban_population,' and 'Rural_population'
youtube <- youtube |>
  relocate(Population, .before = Urban_population)

youtube <- youtube |>
  relocate(Rural_population, .after = Urban_population)

The code above calculates the count of missing values (NAs) in each column of the ‘youtube’ dataset. This step is essential to understand the extent of missing data in the dataset and decide how to handle it appropriately.

The dataset reveals that the majority of columns do not contain any missing values. Among those that do, “subscribers_for_last_30_days” stands out with 337 missing values, followed by variables like Population, Latitude, and Longitude, which also exhibit missing data.

It is worth noting that the presence of ‘nan’ values in character columns like ‘Country’ and ‘category’ went unnoticed during our initial analysis. Additionally, the variable “video_views_for_last_30_days” is of particular significance to our analysis, but it contains 56 missing values. Given its importance and the potential impact on various related variables, addressing these missing values becomes crucial as we proceed with our analysis.

Lets have a closer look at numarical NA variables

In this code, we calculate the average number of subscribers and the count of YouTubers within each category. The results are then arranged in descending order of average subscribers, helping us identify categories that tend to attract more subscribers

# Calculate the average subscribers and count of YouTubers by category
youtube_best_category <- youtube %>%
  group_by(category) %>%
  summarize(
    Avg_subscribers = mean(subscribers, na.rm = TRUE), 
    Number_of_YouTubers = n()
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(Avg_subscribers))

# View the results

In this code, we calculate the average number of subscribers and the count of YouTubers within each country. The results are then arranged in descending order of the number of YouTubers, helping us identify countries with a higher number of YouTubers and, by extension, potentially more subscribers.

# Calculate the average subscribers and count of YouTubers by country
youtube_country_subs <- youtube %>%
  group_by(Country) %>%
  summarize(
    Avg_subscribers = mean(subscribers, na.rm = TRUE), 
    Number_of_YouTubers = n()
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(Number_of_YouTubers))

# View the results

Visualization plays a pivotal role in data analysis, offering a powerful means to both extract insights and communicate findings effectively. Employing a range of visualization techniques and statistical tools, I delved into the data, often uncovering fresh inquiries and revelations that sparked subsequent analyses.

# Summarize the data
summary_df <- youtube %>%
  group_by(channel_type) %>%
  summarise(sum_earnings = sum(highest_yearly_earnings)) %>%
  arrange(desc(sum_earnings))

# Create the bar plot
ggplot(summary_df, aes(x = reorder(channel_type, -sum_earnings), y = sum_earnings, fill = channel_type)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.7, color = "gray") +  # Adjust width and add white borders
  labs(
    x = "Channel Type",
    y = "Total Earnings",
    fill = "Channel Type"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set3") +  # Use a different color palette
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10),  # Adjust text size on the y-axis
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),  # Remove x-axis label
    legend.position = "none"  # Remove legend
  ) +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::comma(sum_earnings), hjust = -0.2), size = 4)  # Add labels to the bars
## Warning in RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(n, pal): n too large, allowed maximum for palette Set3 is 12
## Returning the palette you asked for with that many colors

When considering the total earnings of all YouTubers in the dataset, the Entertainment industry takes the top spot, closely followed by the Music sector

Histogram: Histograms to visualize the distribution of a numeric variable. This can help us understand the central tendency and spread of the data.

# Remove rows with missing values in the subscribers column
clean_data_youtube1 <- youtube[!is.na(youtube$subscribers), ]

# Create the histogram

Scatter Plot: Scatter plots are great for visualizing the relationship between two numeric variables. We can use them to identify trends, correlations, or outliers.

cleaned_data_youtube <- youtube
# Data transformation: Convert 'created_month' to a factor for better visualization
cleaned_data_youtube$created_month <- factor(cleaned_data_youtube$created_month, levels = month.abb)

# Data transformation: Create a new variable 'earnings_range' based on earnings columns
cleaned_data_youtube$earnings_range <- ifelse(cleaned_data_youtube$highest_yearly_earnings >= 1e7, "High", "Low")

# Data transformation: Convert 'subscribers' and 'video_views' to millions for easier interpretation
cleaned_data_youtube$subscribers_millions <- cleaned_data_youtube$subscribers / 1e6
cleaned_data_youtube$video_views_millions <- cleaned_data_youtube$video_views / 1e6

# Scatter plot: Subscribers vs. Video Views
ggplot(cleaned_data_youtube, aes(x = subscribers, y = video_views_millions, color = category)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Subscribers vs. Video Views by Category",
       x = "Subscribers (Millions)",
       y = "Video Views (Millions)",
       color = "Category") +
  theme_minimal()

The plot suggests that there is a positive relationship between the number of subscribers and the number of video views. As the number of subscribers increases, so does the number of video views.

Bar Plot: A bar chart describes the comparisons between the discrete categories.

# Bar plot: Top 10 categories by number of channels
top_categories <- cleaned_data_youtube %>%
  group_by(category) %>%

  head(10)

# Create the bar plot

    x = "Category",
    y = "Number of Channels"

The graphical representation indicates that the number of channels in the Entertainment and Music categories is substantially higher compared to other categories in the dataset.

Heatmap: Heatmaps are useful for displaying relationships and patterns in a matrix of data.

# Calculate the correlation matrix
correlation_matrix <- cor(numeric_vars)

# Create a long-format data frame for the heatmap
correlation_data <- melt(correlation_matrix)

# Create the correlation heatmap
ggplot(data = correlation_data, aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = value, label = round(value, 2))) +
  geom_tile() +
  geom_text(size = 3, color = "black") +  # Add correlation values
  labs(
    title = "Correlation Heatmap of Numeric Variables",
    x = "Variable 1",
    y = "Variable 2"
  ) +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", mid = "white", high = "red", midpoint = 0) +  # Diverging color palette
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "none"  # Remove legend
  )

# Create a summary of channel types

Throughout the modeling journey, revisiting EDA proves instrumental in offering valuable glimpses into the model’s performance and serves as a compass for refining our strategies.

Furthermore, the dynamic nature of data cannot be ignored. With the potential influx of new data or modifications to the existing dataset, a revisitation of the EDA process becomes not just beneficial but often necessary. This ensures that our insights remain pertinent and our models stay abreast of the latest developments.

The iterative voyage of EDA has proven invaluable, enabling the unearthing of profound insights and an ever-evolving grasp of the dataset. This iterative exploration serves as an indispensable bedrock that steers subsequent analyses, shapes the model-building journey, and contributes significantly to informed decision-making.
